        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We use the galaxies' published star-formation rate (SFR), divided by
their half-light radius to obtain a mean SFR surface density, in
combination with the relation between the SFR surface density and the H2 surface density of Kennicutt et al. (2007) to arrive at an estimate for their mean H2 surface density. Using the Milky Way
(alpha_CO=4Mo/pc^2/(K km/s)) and the SMC (alpha_CO=70Mo/pc^2/(K km/s)) as anchor points for an estimate of the variation of alpha_CO(1-0) with metallicity and adopting a 15-20 km/s FWHM of the CO(1-0) emission line, we arrive at peak surface brightnesses of ~10 mK for ESO269-G058 and ESO324-G024 and &lt;~1 mK for KK182. This estimate is in line with what has been detected in slightly more metalrich dwarf galaxies.

With a bandwidth 117.188 MHz and spectral averaging of 16, we achieve a spectral resolution of 1.272 km/s which we further rebin to 2.55 km/s. Using the largest possible angular resolution (6.4 arcseconds), we arrive at a sensitivity of 5 mK for 54 min on source. Including overheads and calibrations, the estimated total time for the three objects is 4.5 hours. The sensitivity will be further improved by averaging over the whole FOV which pushes the sensitivity to ~0.1 mK.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
