    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>We propose to measure the 115GHz CO(1-0) emission line luminosity of 3 late-type dwarf galaxies in the nearby Centaurus A group. These stellar systems have metallicities of 4%, 10%, and 18% of the solar value. To date, the WLM galaxy and the SMC, with metallicities of, respectively, 13% and 20% of solar, are the most metalpoor galaxies in which CO emission has been detected. This hunt for molecular gas in ever more metalpoor stellar systems is interesting in its own right but, given that high-redshift galaxies and local dwarfs share similar metallicities, it also provides us with a means of studying the physical conditions under which star formation proceeded in the early universe.

The CO to molecular hydrogen conversion factor has been studied in environments with metallicities above 13% of solar. The envisaged ALMA observations are a crucial first step in pushing the
constraints on the CO to H_2 conversion factor down to metallicities of 4% of solar. Since CO is the most direct available tracer of molecular gas, studying its metallicity dependence is imperative for a proper assessment of the molecular gas content of galaxies, both in the nearby and in the high-redshift universe.</prp:abstract>
